text:
Beware of fake software ads on Google Search!

Hackers use #Google Ads to direct users searching for popular software, such as KeePass #Password Manager and Notepad++, to malicious copycats that distribute #malware.

Its not like they leave maliscious app on the store by purpose. in fact the absolut majority of the risk with google apps, is that play protect scans the initial upload and official updates off the app. it may be clean. however the app itself, may use backchannel updates, where when you run it it pulls updates directly from a source, circumventing play protect. however by restricting the permissions of the app to bare minimum you can mitigate alot of future risks.

text:
A #vulnerability in Synology's DSM has been revealed, allowing attackers to remotely hijack admin accounts.

Learn how to safeguard your data: https://thehackernews.com/2023/10/new-admin-takeover-vulnerability.html

#hacking #cybersecurity

D-Link confirms data breach. Low-sensitivity data exposed from an old system due to an employee falling for a phishing attack.

Find details here: https://thehackernews.com/2023/10/d-link-confirms-data-breach-employee.html

text:
Ukraine's CERT-UA discovered threat actors targeting 11 telecom providers between May and September 2023. The attacks caused service interruptions, and they used programs called POEMGATE and POSEIDON to control telecom hosts.

Learn more: https://thehackernews.com/2023/10/cert-ua-reports-11-ukrainian-telecom.html

text:
Discover the dangerous capabilities of SpyNote, an #Android banking trojan. It records audio, logs keystrokes, SMS messages, and captures screenshots without detection.

Find out more about this invasive spyware: https://thehackernews.com/2023/10/spynote-beware-of-this-android-trojan.html

#cybersecurity #infosec #malware

'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': "Jefferson Clark So...
How is SpyNote installed?
Through the official app store?
Is it side loaded, did the user give it permissions?
Was the user tricked?

I'm not saying that the Play Store doesn't contain applications with crap, we've seen that multiple times before.
But chances are a lot lower than when you're side loading or using other unofficial stores.

In any case, the biggest security protection is your own knowledge.
Simply don't install shit you dont need or know what is.
Don't give applications permissions you see no reason they have.

Huawei and other brands that doesn't come with Google Play Services are more at risk than phones with Google Play Services.
But I doubt you'd be able to hold a Chinese company responsible.

The biggest security difference between Google Android and Apple iOS is, that Google runs Android on phones by multiple brands, allows side loading and custom stores...
